      "message": "That\u0027s going to be annoying. Going back to the question on https://skia-review.googlesource.com/c/skia/+/233565:\nI trust Ben better than my own understanding (and admittedly don\u0027t know all the details of C++\u0027s \"abstract machine\" and all the reorderings it allows) but I don\u0027t understand why the compiler can omit the entire block even if sk_abort_no_print() isn\u0027t marked noreturn. It seems to me on an intuitive level (perhaps a fatal error when it comes to C++) that if there *might* be a path through sk_abort_no_print() that doesn\u0027t return then the compiler can\u0027t toss the whole block. Is the compiler allowed to assume all functions not marked noreturn will always return? \n\n*If* we could put a __builtin_unreachable back at the end of SK_ABORT then we wouldn\u0027t have the return problem and with this definition of SkUNREACHABLE would always cause a deliberate abort where it is used.",
